> various tricks<p>They actually present (approximately) a very simple construct that is used to speed the interpreters up:<p><pre><code>   void labels[] = { &&ADD, &&SUB . . . };
   ...
   goto labels[ vpc++ ];
   ADD:
      ...
      goto labels[ vpc++ ];
</code></pre>
instead of<p><pre><code>    ...
    switch ( *vpc++ )
    {
    case ADD:
         ....
         break;
    case SUB:
</code></pre>
It&#x27;s not really hard. The only problem is that the former is not a standard C and not present in MSVC. See<p><a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/6421433/address-of-labels-msvc" rel="nofollow">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/6421433/address-of-labels...</a><p>&quot;Erlang does (that) for building on Windows. They use MSVC for most of the build, and then GCC for one file to make use of the labels-as-values extension. The resulting object code is then hacked to be made compatible with the MSVC linker.&quot;<p>It obviously mattered enough for Erlang developers to use GCC even for just that critical piece of C code. It doesn&#x27;t mean that it has to be regularly used in every code (not every switch is executed the way the main interpreter loop is).

